The issue is that when `lastIndex` *is* `indexOfMax` (which in your case happens when `lastIndex` is `3` and the first four elements are `-22, 1, -15, 7`), you never enter the code that resets `i` for the next pass through the loop. Instead, you just continue incrementing `i` (and potentially updating `indexOfMax`) until the loop exits.

To fix that, you need to change this:

```
            }else if (i == lastIndex &amp;&amp; lastIndex &gt; 0){
```

to this:

```
            }
            if (i == lastIndex &amp;&amp; lastIndex &gt; 0){
```

(I guess the reason you wrote `else if` was so as to skip swapping `inputArray[lastIndex]` with `inputArray[indexOfMax]` when that&#39;s a no-op? The problem is that this block includes more than just that swap code, so you&#39;re skipping too much in that case.)

---

All of that being said, I feel compelled to point out that your code would be much simpler and clearer if, instead of using a single `for`-loop where you keep resetting `i`, you used nested loops, like so:

```
    public static void selectionSort(final int[] array){
        for (int lastIndex = array.length - 1; lastIndex &gt; 0; --lastIndex) {
            int indexOfMax = 0;
            for (int i = 1; i &lt;= lastIndex; ++i) {
                if (array[i] &gt; array[indexOfMax]) {
                    indexOfMax = i;
                }
            }
            final int temp = array[lastIndex];
            array[lastIndex] = array[indexOfMax];
            array[indexOfMax] = temp;
        }
    }
```

